---
/**
 * The defense nexus — the interactive companion to the full report
 * (docs/defense-nexus.md, #258). The essay holds one discipline: geographic
 * adjacency, a capability, and a named market segment are an *inferred* connection,
 * never a finding. The map makes that literal — the campus footprint and the JSMC
 * (US-owned) footprint with the gap between them measured off the cited parcels
 * (~5.5 mi, not the "two miles" the prose first reached for). Reuses the walk's
 * island-over-SSR pattern; pays off into the full cited essay.
 */
import ReportShell from "../../../../layouts/ReportShell.astro";
import DefenseNexusMap from "../../../../components/islands/DefenseNexusMap.tsx";
import RedactionReveal from "../../../../components/RedactionReveal.astro";
import { buildDefenseNexus } from "../../../../lib/defenseNexus";
import type { TeardownRedaction } from "../../../../lib/teardown";
import { withSite } from "../../../../lib/site";

const dn = buildDefenseNexus();
const m = dn.metrics;

// "What would close it" — the one disclosable fact that isn't in the record (#267).
const closeIt: TeardownRedaction = {
  label: "[open] · the facility’s authorization posture",
  summary: "What would actually connect this campus — or clear it?",
  lock: "No FedRAMP / DoD authorization record for the Lima facility appears in the corpus, and the public-records request for any County ⇄ DoD / GDLS communication returned “no records.” The IL-6 capability belongs to Google everywhere it operates; the posture of this facility is undocumented.",
  cite: "response-index.yaml item 2 — “No records” · docs/defense-nexus.md",
  read: "One disclosable fact would close it: the Lima facility’s FedRAMP / DoD impact-level posture, or a dated County ⇄ DoD / GDLS communication. Neither is in the record. Proximity is not connection — the gap stays measured, and empty.",
  href: withSite("/docs/defense-nexus"),
};
---

<ReportShell
  title="The defense nexus"
  description="A federal plant a few miles from the campus, a developer cleared to SECRET, an industry that hosts the CIA — three true facts that don't, combined, make a finding. Map the footprints, measure the gap, hold the question open."
  eyebrow="Extension narrative · #233 · the defense thread"
  h1="What the corridor shows, and what it can't"
  fullReportHref="/docs/defense-nexus"
>
  <Fragment slot="lead">
      <p class="section-lead">
        There is a defense installation near the campus, the developer has the
        credentials to do defense work, and an industry witness told a state committee
        that hosting the government is a normal line of business. Each of those is
        <strong>true</strong>. None of them — alone or together — shows that the Lima
        campus does defense work. The map below holds both at once: the facts are real,
        and the gap between them is <em>{dn.available ? `${m.nearestMi.toFixed(1)} measured miles` : "real distance"}</em>
        of city, drawn but never crossed.
      </p>
  </Fragment>

    {
      dn.available && (
        <section class="walk-interactive" aria-label="The campus and JSMC footprints, and the measured gap">
          <h2 class="walk-explore-h">Three facts, one map — pick one and read what it does and doesn't reach</h2>
          <div class="dn-surface">
            <DefenseNexusMap client:only="react" data={dn} />
            <noscript>
              <div class="dil-noscript">
                The map needs JavaScript — the same facts, footprints and the measured
                gap are in the table below.
              </div>
            </noscript>
          </div>
        </section>
      )
    }

    {/* Plain-text fallback. Open by default so no-JS readers get the content immediately;
        the inline script collapses it when JS is present so it doesn't double the island. */}
    <details open class="dn-fallback" id="dn-fallback">
      <summary class="dn-fallback-summary">The three facts in plain text — and the measured gap</summary>
      <table class="dtable dn-table">
        <caption>
          Each row is <code>[verified]</code>. None of them, and not their sum, is a
          connection — that stays <code>[open]</code>.
        </caption>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">What's confirmed</th>
            <th scope="col">What it actually is</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {
            dn.facts.map((f) => (
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <strong>{f.title}</strong>
                  <span class="dn-td-cite">{f.cite}</span>
                </td>
                <td>{f.body}</td>
              </tr>
            ))
          }
          {
            dn.available && (
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <strong>The measured gap</strong>
                  <span class="dn-td-cite">computed from geo/campus + geo/jsmc</span>
                </td>
                <td>
                  Nearest parcels <strong>~{m.nearestMi.toFixed(1)} mi</strong> apart; centers
                  <strong> ~{m.centroidMi.toFixed(1)} mi</strong>. The JSMC footprint is
                  {" "}~{Math.round(m.jsmcAcres)} acres across {m.jsmcParcels} US-owned parcels.
                  The campus and the plant share a city and a corridor study area — not
                  adjoining land.
                </td>
              </tr>
            )
          }
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </details>
    {dn.available && (
      <script is:inline>
        document.getElementById("dn-fallback")?.removeAttribute("open");
      </script>
    )}

    <div class="callout callout--open">
      <p class="callout-title">Where this stops</p>
      <p>
        A defense nexus is not a finding of this record. It is a question the record
        raises by what it contains — a federal plant down the corridor, a developer
        cleared to SECRET, a procurement order, an industry that hosts the CIA — and
        cannot answer by what it withholds. The honest end is the open one: one
        disclosable fact would close it, and it is the one the record doesn't carry.
      </p>
      <RedactionReveal redaction={closeIt} />
    </div>

    <Fragment slot="full-report">
      the IL-6 credential, the AWS testimony naming the Department of War and the CIA,
      Executive Order 14265, the relator's own framing of the thread as “likely
      speculative,” and why the “no records” response forecloses one avenue without
      proving the connection absent or present
    </Fragment>
</ReportShell>
